St. Gregory. It is true that the Sacramentary contains the name of a St. Gregory in two places3 but even if there be not a copyist's error between the two names Georyz'us and Greyorz'us-an error of frequent occurrence in the manu- scripts—it cannot, in any case, be St. Gregory the Pope, as the saint in question is a martyr. Resides this, the Pope of that name decreed that the prayer Hane iyitur oblationem, in the Canon of the Mass, should from this time forward conclude with the words, diesque nostros in tua pace disponas atque ab aeterna damnatione nos eripi et in electorum tuorum jubeas φερε numerari. It is true, indeed, that the Canon of the Mass is missing in the Verona manuscript. It must have been at the beginning, in the part now lost. The prayer Home τρίταν, however, occurs a certain number of times in the remainder of the text, yet never once with the Gregorian ending. As we do not find elsewhere any other indication of a date posterior to that of St. Gregory‚ we shall not be far wrong in attributing the old Veronese Sacramentary to the middle or end of the sixth century.

It must be a purely Roman book, not only because of the absence of any traces of Gallie-an elements in it, or because in the State prayers it always makes mention of the Roman Empire with peculiar loyalty, but because it exhibits on every page those topographical touches which enable us to distinguish between a text drawn up for the Church of Rome locally, and one which is merely in con- formity with the Roman use. The rubrics which announce the festivals of the saints often designate the place of the station with marked topographical precision.
